problem:
Given the function $f(x)=|x+1|-|x-2|$.
$(1)$ Find the solution set of the inequality $f(x)\geqslant 1$;
$(2)$ If the solution set of the inequality $f(x)\geqslant x^{2}-x+m$ is non-empty, find the range of values for $m$.

solution:
Solution:
$(1)$ Since $f(x)=|x+1|-|x-2|=\begin{cases} -3, & x < -1 \\ 2x-1, & -1\leqslant x\leqslant 2 \\ 3, & x > 2\end{cases}$, and $f(x)\geqslant 1$,
Therefore, when $-1\leqslant x\leqslant 2$, we have $2x-1\geqslant 1$, solving this gives $1\leqslant x\leqslant 2$;
When $x > 2$, $3\geqslant 1$ always holds, thus $x > 2$;
Overall, the solution set of the inequality $f(x)\geqslant 1$ is $\boxed{\{x|x\geqslant 1\}}$.

$(2)$ The original expression is equivalent to the existence of $x\in\mathbb{R}$ such that $f(x)-x^{2}+x\geqslant m$ holds,
which means $m\leqslant \max[f(x)-x^{2}+x]$, let $g(x)=f(x)-x^{2}+x$.
From $(1)$, we know $g(x)=\begin{cases} -x^{2}+x-3, & x\leqslant -1 \\ -x^{2}+3x-1, & -1 < x < 2 \\ -x^{2}+x+3, & x\geqslant 2\end{cases}$,
When $x\leqslant -1$, $g(x)=-x^{2}+x-3$, it opens downwards, and the axis of symmetry is $x= \dfrac {1}{2} > -1$,
Therefore, $g(x)\leqslant g(-1)=-1-1-3=-5$;
When $-1 < x < 2$, $g(x)=-x^{2}+3x-1$, it opens downwards, and the axis of symmetry is $x= \dfrac {3}{2}\in(-1,2)$,
Therefore, $g(x)\leqslant g\left( \dfrac {3}{2}\right)=- \dfrac {9}{4}+ \dfrac {9}{2}-1= \dfrac {5}{4}$;
When $x\geqslant 2$, $g(x)=-x^{2}+x+3$, it opens downwards, and the axis of symmetry is $x= \dfrac {1}{2} < 2$,
Therefore, $g(x)\leqslant g(2)=-4+2+3=1$;
Overall, $\max g(x)= \dfrac {5}{4}$,
Therefore, the range of values for $m$ is $\boxed{(-\infty, \dfrac {5}{4}]}$.

